[4.1 Join Expressions]
	(4.1.1 The Natural Join)
		- "natural join" operation
			-> operates on two relations and produces a relation as the result.
				ex)
					SELECT name, course_id
					FROM student
					NATURAL JOIN takes;

					(equals to)
					SELECT name, course_id
					FROM student, takes
					WHERE student.ID = takes.ID;

			* rarely used in modern DB SQL.

	(4.1.2 Join Conditions)
		- "on" condition
			-> allows a general predicate over the relations being joined.
			-> "ON" rather than "WHERE"

				ex)
					SELECT *
					FROM student
					JOIN takes
					ON student.ID = takes.ID;

	(4.1.3 Outer Joins)
		- "left outer join"
			-> preserves tuples only in the relation named before the "left outer join" operation.

		- "right outer join"
			-> preserves tuples only in the relation named after the "right outer join" operation.

		- "full outer join"
			-> preserves tuples in both relations.

	(4.1.4 Join Types and Conditions)
		- normal joins are called "inner joins" in SQL.

		* "join" clause used without the "outer" prefix, is the "inner join"

			ex)
				SELECT *
				FROM student
				JOIN takes using (ID);

				(is equal to)

				SELECT *
				FROM student
				INNER JOIN takes using (ID);

		


